  "prompt": "What is a ionic bond? What are some examples?",
  "response": "## Ionic Bonds: A Definition\n\nAn ionic bond is a type of chemical bond formed through the **electrostatic attraction** between oppositely charged ions. These ions are formed when one atom **transfers** one or more electrons to another atom.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Electron Transfer:** One atom (typically a metal) *loses* electrons and becomes a positively charged ion (cation). Another atom (typically a nonmetal) *gains* these electrons and becomes a negatively charged ion (anion).\n*   **Electrostatic Attraction:** The oppositely charged ions are then strongly attracted to each other due to their opposite charges (positive and negative).  This attraction is what holds them together in the ionic bond.\n\n**Key Characteristics of Ionic Compounds:**\n\n*   **High Melting and Boiling Points:**  Strong electrostatic forces require a lot of energy to overcome, leading to high melting and boiling points.\n*   **Crystalline Structure:** Ions arrange themselves in a regular, repeating pattern called a crystal lattice, maximizing attractions and minimizing repulsions.\n*   **Conductivity:**  Ionic compounds conduct electricity when molten (liquid) or dissolved in water because the ions are then free to move and carry charge. However, they do not conduct electricity in the solid state because the ions are fixed in the lattice.\n*   **Brittleness:**  If the layers of ions in a crystal lattice are shifted, ions with the same charge can come into close proximity, resulting in repulsion and causing the crystal to shatter.\n*   **Solubility in Polar Solvents:** Many ionic compounds are soluble in polar solvents like water because the polar solvent molecules can interact favorably with the charged ions, weakening the ionic bonds and allowing the ions to disperse.\n\n## Examples of Ionic Bonds and Compounds:\n\nHere are some common examples of compounds formed with ionic bonds:\n\n1.  **Sodium Chloride (NaCl) - Table Salt:**\n    *   Sodium (Na) loses one electron to form Na<sup>+</sup> (a cation).\n    *   Chlorine (Cl) gains one electron to form Cl<sup>-</sup> (an anion).\n    *   Na<sup>+</sup> and Cl<sup>-</sup> are attracted to each other, forming the ionic compound NaCl.\n\n2.  **Magnesium Oxide (MgO):**\n    *   Magnesium (Mg) loses two electrons to form Mg<sup>2+</sup> (a cation).\n    *   Oxygen (O) gains two electrons to form O<sup>2-</sup> (an anion).\n    *   Mg<sup>2+</sup> and O<sup>2-</sup> are attracted to each other, forming the ionic compound MgO.\n\n3.  **Potassium Iodide (KI):**\n    *   Potassium (K) loses one electron to form K<sup>+</sup> (a cation).\n    *   Iodine (I) gains one electron to form I<sup>-</sup> (an anion).\n    *   K<sup>+</sup> and I<sup>-</sup> are attracted to each other, forming the ionic compound KI.\n\n4.  **Calcium Chloride (CaCl<sub>2</sub>):**\n    *   Calcium (Ca) loses two electrons to form Ca<sup>2+</sup> (a cation).\n    *   Each chlorine (Cl) atom gains one electron to form Cl<sup>-</sup> (an anion). Two chloride ions are needed to balance the charge of the calcium ion.\n    *   Ca<sup>2+</sup> and two Cl<sup>-</sup> ions are attracted to each other, forming the ionic compound CaCl<sub>2</sub>.\n\n5.  **Lithium Fluoride (LiF):**\n    *   Lithium (Li) loses one electron to form Li<sup>+</sup> (a cation).\n    *   Fluorine (F) gains one electron to form F<sup>-</sup> (an anion).\n    *   Li<sup>+</sup> and F<sup>-</sup> are attracted to each other, forming the ionic compound LiF.\n\n**In summary:**  Ionic bonds are fundamental chemical bonds based on the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions.  These ions are formed through the transfer of electrons from one atom to another, typically between metals and nonmetals. The resulting compounds have characteristic properties like high melting points, crystalline structures, and conductivity when molten or dissolved.\n",
